Power Management & Voltage Regulation
⚠️ Critical Power Warning
Do not use the +12V rail to power the Arduino Nano directly. While the Nano technical specs suggest it can handle higher voltages, the onboard regulator is small and prone to overheating. Instead, use a dedicated 5V voltage regulator to ensure system longevity.

Recommended Components
You can use either an L7805 or a 78L05 regulator:

L7805: Best for projects with higher current demands (e.g., driving many LEDs or multiple ICs).

78L05: A smaller, "TO-92" package suitable for low-current applications.

Biasing the TL072 Op-Amp
Use the output from your 5V regulator to create the 2.5V reference voltage for the TL072 op-amp. This ensures that your signal offset remains stable and relative to your microcontroller's logic level.

Why This Matters
Heat Dissipation: By dropping the voltage externally, you prevent the Arduino's onboard regulator from working too hard and burning out.

Component Safety: It isolates the sensitive microcontroller from potential noise or spikes on the 12V power rail.

Precision: Using the regulated 5V source for your op-amp reference is significantly more accurate than using an unregulated supply.

